# The docstring is the contract

This test's docstring defines its scope: exactly what the test is meant to
verify. Your job is to make the test pass and make it verify exactly that scope
-- no more, no less. The docstring is authoritative: do NOT re-derive the
intended scope from the commands or the implementation. Read the docstring and
take it as given.

The docstring is READ-ONLY. Never edit it (the one narrow exception is in
"# Correcting an outdated tutorial block" below).

# If the test fails

You can record multiple kinds of changes -- they are not mutually exclusive (one
entry per kind, not per individual edit):

- "FIX_TEST": fix the test code (including fixtures).
- "FIX_IMPL": fix the program being tested.

Each change has a status: "SUCCEEDED" if the fix worked, "FAILED" if you tried
but could not complete it, or "BLOCKED" if the issue needs larger intervention
beyond this task. If you cannot determine what is wrong, report no changes.

When deciding whether to fix the test or the implementation, the docstring is the
arbiter: the correct behavior is whatever the docstring's scope says it should
be. If the implementation diverges from the documented scope, fix the
implementation; if the test asserts something outside the documented scope, fix
the test.

# If the test succeeds - or after you fixed a failing test

Make the test verify exactly its docstring scope -- check it in BOTH directions:

- Coverage (forward): is everything the scope calls for actually verified? If the
  scope says to observe a real effect (e.g. that an agent is running in a given
  directory, not merely that the command exited 0), the test must observe it. Add
  any missing verification the scope requires.

- Trace (backward): does every assertion trace back to the scope? An assertion
  that verifies something the scope does not mention is gold-plating: it adds
  brittleness without verifying documented behavior. REMOVE it.

A test that already verifies exactly its scope needs no change: leaving the
changes object empty is a correct, good outcome, NOT a failure. Do not add
assertions merely to be thorough -- the scope fixes what "thorough" means here.

Removing or simplifying an over-fitted assertion is a real improvement, exactly
as valuable as adding a missing one -- both are recorded under "IMPROVE_TEST".

You may add a separate pytest function for an unhappy/error path when the
docstring's scope includes that failure mode. Only do so when the scope calls for
it -- not to manufacture extra coverage.

If you make improvements (adding, removing, or restructuring), record a change
under the key "IMPROVE_TEST". If an improvement needs a larger-scale
intervention, use status "BLOCKED". If the test already verifies exactly its
scope, leave the changes object empty.

# Correcting an outdated tutorial block

Some tests are anchored to a documentation tutorial: their docstring begins with
a "Tutorial block:" section holding a shell snippet verbatim, kept in sync with
libs/mngr/imbue/mngr/resources/mega_tutorial.sh. This block is the ONLY part of
any docstring you may edit, and only in one case: the block is genuinely wrong or
outdated relative to how the command actually behaves now.

When that happens, update BOTH the "Tutorial block:" section in the docstring and
the corresponding block in mega_tutorial.sh (keep them identical, modulo leading
whitespace), and record the change under the key "FIX_TUTORIAL". This should be
rare. The "Scope:" prose and every other docstring are always off-limits. Tests
without a "Tutorial block:" section have no tutorial to fix.

# Cross-cutting setup blockers

Some problems can only be fixed by a substantial, shared setup change that is out
of scope for a single test -- for example, the suite mocking an agent with a
`sleep` command instead of a real fake-agent fixture, a missing shared helper, or
a dependency on credentials absent from the environment (e.g. cloud credentials
for a provider test). You see only one test, so you cannot tell whether such
setup is duplicated across the suite, nor fix it suite-wide.

When you hit one, do NOT paper over it with a brittle local hack. Instead:

1. Leave a comment at the relevant spot in the code, on its own line, in exactly
   this form so a later step can find it:

     # FIXME(tmr): <one-line description of the shared setup change needed>

2. Record a change (typically FIX_TEST or IMPROVE_TEST) with status "BLOCKED" and
   explain the needed setup change in summary_markdown.

A later integration step collects these comments, resolves the ones it can verify
suite-wide, and surfaces the rest to the user. Your job is only to flag them
clearly -- do not attempt the suite-wide change yourself.

# Examining the test output

After each test run, examine any output the test produced (logs, a CLI
transcript in the test output directory, captured stdout/stderr). Look for
unexpected output such as warnings, deprecation notices, or error messages that
were not caught by the test assertions. If you find something concerning,
consider whether the test should assert on it (only if the scope covers it), or
whether the implementation should be fixed to avoid the warning.

# Committing your changes

IMPORTANT: Each change kind MUST get its own separate commit. Changes of the same
kind should be combined in one commit. The commit message MUST start with the kind
in brackets. Examples:

  [FIX_TEST] Fix assertion to check exit code instead of stdout
  [FIX_IMPL] Add missing timeout parameter to create command
  [IMPROVE_TEST] Remove assertion outside the documented scope

This means if you make both a FIX_TEST and a FIX_IMPL change, you should have
exactly two commits. Do NOT mix different kinds in the same commit.

